seek truthful labeling of food products along with warnings 
regarding sodium cholesterol and the additive content of packaged 
food products 
the ama would call upon the federal trade commission to 
investigate the advertising practices of food manufacturers who 
present their products as low in sodium or cholesterol under the 
second plan submitted by dr louis f alfano a delegate from the 
american society of abdominal surgeons 
both resolutions were referred to an ama committee that was to 
vote on whether to recommend that the associations house of 
delegates adopt them as policy 
a critic said the measures were vague and would provide useless 
and misleading information to millions of people over age 60 whose 
cholesterol levels cannot be altered by what they eat 
but supporters say many other consumers would be wellserved by 
such labeling 
health conscious consumers are often misled by the advertising 
and labeling of common food products such as canned soups labeled as 
low sodium which contain a substantial sodium content but are only 
lower in sodium than the manfacturers regular line of soups 
alfano said 
the ama can clear up the confusion by asking the us food and 
drug administration to assist the consumer by requiring more 
specific food labeling he told committee members 
dr arnold briet an alternate delegate presented the california 
plan and said he supported alfanos resolution 
cholesterol is a waxy substance that can contribute to clogged 
arteries and heart disease depending on what type of fatty proteins 
carry it through the blood 
it is produced naturally in the body and develops from eating 
food with saturated fats or pure cholesterol such as eggs butter 
and animal fat 
the fda has implemented labeling standards that allow foods to be 
billed as cholesterolreduced even though they still have large 
amounts of cholesterol briet said 
nowhere do they require the source of the oils to be labeled 
he said 
some plant fats such as coconut and palm oils contain high 
amounts of saturated fatty acids that can help cholesterol form and 
food manufacturers like nabisco brands inc and quaker oats co have 
taken steps to remove such oils from their products 
dr henry mineur an internist and delegate from new jersey 
noted that there is an ongoing debate over socalled good and 
bad cholesterol he said the proposals would be useless unless 
they called for labels to differentiate between the two 
quit this damn hype that all types of cholesterol are bad for 
everybody mineur told the committee 
bad cholesterol is carried through the bloodstream by 
lowdensity lipoproteins linked to the buildup of harmful deposits 
in the arteries 
good cholesterol is carried by highdensity lipoproteins that 
researchers believe suck up excess cholesterol in the bloodstream 
furthermore mineur argued reducing cholesterol consumption is 
only useful for those under age 60 theres no evidence that people 
older than that can lower their risk of heart disease by altering 
their intake of fats he said 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

