sulfur dioxide emissions which have taken the principal blame for 
acid rain 
buoyed by its first profitable year since 1981 bethlehem pledged 
in 1987 to reduce emissions the new agreement calls for more 
extensive measures including a 40 million modernization of a 
chemical recovery plant to reduce emissions of sulfur dioxide and 
toxic pollutants mainly benzene and hydrogen cyanide 
benzene can cause leukemia and other cancers anemia and other 
health problems hydrogen cyanide can kill if inhaled in high 
concentrations 
bethlehem also promised to repair leaking walls and flues at a 
cost of 24 million to cut down on the black smoke belching from 
three smokestacks 
by 1994 the cleanup should result in reductions of 54 percent in 
particulates 67 percent in sulfur dioxide 50 percent in volatile 
organic compounds that create ozone and 30 percent in benzene 
officials said 
