<TEXT>
the conciergerie the dank and forbidding stone 
prison where victims of the french revolution spent their final 
moments opened to the public tuesday in all its former gloom and 
grandeur 
queen marie antoinette occupied a cell on the ground floor for 10 
weeks in 1793 hoping her supporters would come up with enough money 
to buy her freedom 
she waited in vain and went to her death at the guillotine on 
oct 16 1793 
the cell she shared with her jailer later was turned into a 
chapel as a shrine to her memory but a replica of the cell has been 
recreated nearby and is decorated with wallpaper embossed with the 
royal blue and gold lily emblems that covered the walls 200 years 
ago 
maximilien robespierre who sent thousands of heads rolling 
during his 12month reign of terror against counterrevolutionaries 
spent his final hours a few cells away on july 28 1794 
his death warrant arrived about 10 am and he was carted away 
to the guillotine in midafternoon michel colardelle of the 
culture ministry said during a tour of the restored landmark 
overlooking the seine the spot is marked by a simple black marble 
plaque 
admirers of robespierre known as the incorruptible say history 
has not done him justice 
he has been made to bear all the guilt of the terror said 
former health minister leon schwartzenberg one of several public 
figures eager to rehabilitate robespierres memory 
all revolutions are characterized by excess of some sort 
otherwise they would not be revolutions he said 
no one however can accuse the french of not paying tribute to 
robespierres victims and others who died during the turbulent 
events 
a small room on the second floor is devoted entirely to their 
memory its four walls are covered with framed lists in 
alphabetical order of the 2780 aristocrats gardeners shoemakers 
doctors and clergymen found guilty by the revolutionary tribunal and 
beheaded within three days the verdict was either guilty or 
acquittal there were no appeals 
some names are familiar like charlotte corday who stabbed 
jeanpaul marat in his bath others like f perrin gardener are 
not 
a short film with english subtitles helps visitors follow the 
events and depicts daily life at the prison 
ordinary prisoners shared the squalor of cold cells littered with 
filthy straw the wealthy bought their way into cells furnished with 
beds and sometimes even desks where many an aristocrat penned his 
memoirs 
also recreated are the quarters where the condemned were taken to 
have their shirts ripped wide and the napes of their necks shaved so 
the guillotines blade would cut cleanly 
prisoners were allowed to circulate freely during the day in the 
womens courtyard despite their predicament many privileged ladies 
managed to keep up with fashion trends and even groomed themselves 
without the help of maids 
marie antoinette in her final days even learned to put up her 
own hair said jean chalon author of a recent biography 
the 375000 renovation of the conciergerie is one of several 
refurbishing projects linked to bicentennial celebrations 
</TEXT>
