<TEXT>
a house committee on tuesday passed legislation 
that would limit civil contempt of court jailings in the district of 
columbia a bill designed to help a mother who has been jailed 22 
months in a child custody dispute 
elizabeth morgan a prominent plastic surgeon was jailed by dc 
superior court judge herbert dixon after she refused to tell him 
where she had sent her sixyearold daughter hilary he has said 
repeatedly he will not lift his contempt citation until she gives 
the information 
morgan has been trying to prevent any visit between the child and 
eric foretich the girls father morgan has accused foretich her 
former husband of sexually abusing the child he has repeatedly 
denied it 
the legislation designed to apply retroactively to morgans 
case would limit civil contempt jailings in the district to 12 
months unless the judge in the case changes the charge to criminal 
contempt a charge that would require a trial people could be held 
on criminal contempt charges during the trial but not longer than 
18 months 
the bill also requires that a different judge hear the criminal 
contempt charges 
we do not seek to place a limitation on the amount of time an 
individual can be sentenced to serve if convicted of criminal 
contempt said rep stan parris rva a cosponsor of the bill 
passed by the district of columbia committee our aim was to 
preserve the basic right of individuals to due process under the 
law 
nine of the members of the committee voted for the legislation 
with only rep mervyn dymally dcalif voting against it parris 
said the legislation is expected to go before the full house next 
week 
the panels action came a day after dixon ruled again that the 
mother must remain behind bars until she discloses the whereabouts 
of her daughter or turns the child over to the citys foster care 
department 
a district of columbia appeals court panel had directed dixon to 
justify his december 1988 decision to keep morgan in jail 
dixons latest ruling will now be reviewed by that threejudge 
panel 
foretichs attorney elaine mittleman said tuesday in a 
statement civil contempt does not transform into criminal 
contempt a crime such as obstruction of justice is much more 
suited to dr morgans offenses than is criminal contempt 
</TEXT>
