<TEXT>
president bush welcomes the soviet unions 
increased willingness to allow verification of nuclear weapons 
reductions and plans to build on that in new initiatives the chief 
us negotiator said tuesday 
negotiator richard burt declined to discuss bushs proposals in 
detail but said we have noticed that the soviets have taken a 
much more open and constructive approach on verification in recent 
years 
bushs proposal came monday in washington as the superpowers 
resumed strategic arms reduction talks in geneva after a sevenmonth 
recess 
the president said the united states and soviet union should 
begin testing verification procedures during negotiations on 
reducing longrange nuclear forces rather than waiting until a pact 
is completed 
such steps could involve trial inspections at each others 
missile sites and discussions about equipment needed for 
verification which bush said could be the most complex issue facing 
negotiators 
tuesdays editions of the washington post quoted an unidentified 
official in washington as saying negotiators plan to suggest 
aroundtheclock monitoring of some ballistic missile factories and 
onsite checks of missile warheads to start before any new 
agreement the proposal also was reported to include a ban on some 
missile flight tests 
burt said that another aim of bushs plan is to build support for 
senate ratification of a future arms treaty 
several superpower arms control treaties including the 1979 salt 
ii pact on limiting longrange nuclear arsenals remained unratified 
because the senate decided the verification provisions were lax 
burt said progress on verification would not become a condition 
in the start talks 
we will continue to move on all fronts he said we are not 
proposing these measures as a takeitorleaveit package 
the talks aimed at reducing us and soviet longrange bombers 
missiles and nuclear submarines by 30 percent to 50 percent are the 
latest round in negotiations that began four years ago 
burt said at the news conference that their aim is to speed 
resolution of outstanding issues and give added momentum toward 
completing a treaty 
under soviet president mikhail s gorbachevs philosophy of more 
openness moscow has allowed western experts to tour a soviet 
chemical weapons site for the first time as part of efforts to 
negotiate a global ban 
us and soviet scientists also have exchanged visits to each 
others nuclear testing sites to examine ways of monitoring two 
1970s treaties limiting atomic blasts that the senate never approved 
burt confirmed that the bush administrations review of arms 
policy did not result in a change in the strategic defense 
initiative which calls for spacebased missile defenses a divisive 
issue since arms talks began 
he rejected soviet attempts to link a start treaty to agreement 
on what washington says would be crippling curbs on sdi 
on monday yuri nazarkin head of the soviet delegation to the 
talks met with burt for 80 minutes at the us mission 
nazarkin spoke of a good start and held out the prospect of 
unspecified soviet initiatives 
the talks are to last six to seven weeks 
in detailed negotiations starting wednesday with a full meeting 
of both delegations burt will lead the us team and lem masterkov 
will continue as soviet negotiator under nazarkin 
disputes have developed over moscows demand for including 
seabased cruise missiles in the treaty and washingtons call for a 
ban on mobile missiles 
at earlier talks boths sides agreed to lower ceilings of 6000 
nuclear warheads and 1600 delivery vehicles missiles and bombers 
for each side 
