<DOCNO> AP890620-0144 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
house and senate negotiators on tuesday 
resolved a key difference in bills to remove all federal price 
controls on natural gas by jan 1 1993 
the compromise bill is expected to be signed by president bush 
within a few weeks it is not expected to have a noticeable effect 
on retail prices for natural gas because most gas under controls 
already is selling below the official ceilings 
the energy industry supports decontrol while some consumer 
groups oppose it some other consumer groups however have taken 
what amounts to a neutral position 
the only difference between the original house and senate bills 
was in treatment of natural gas from newly drilled wells the senate 
version had no provision for early deregulation of gas from such 
wells whereas the house wanted to lift price controls on them 
retroactive to march 23 1989 
in a compromise the negotiators agreed that gas from wells 
drilled after the date of enactment of the legislation would be 
deregulated on may 15 1991 all other gas not already decontrolled 
would be freed from the federal ceilings upon the renegotiation of 
sales contracts or jan 1 1993 whichever comes first 
about twothirds of the nations natural gas was deregulated by 
the 1978 natural gas policy act 
natural gas accounts for about onequarter of the nations energy 
use 
the bush administration strongly supports complete decontrol 
contending that it will stimulate more exploration for a fuel source 
needed to limit dependence on foreign oil 
the house passed its original bill in april while the senate 
bill was passed earlier this month the compromise bill must be 
voted on by both houses again before it is sent to the white house 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

