<TEXT>
the vatican appointed lay businessman and 
bankers to manage its scandaltainted bank tuesday ending the 
20year presidency of american archbishop paul c marcinkus 
in principle laymen should be more competent in financial 
affairs than clerics said vatican spokesman joaquin navarro 
he identified an american businessman and bankers from italy 
spain switzerland and west germany who were named to the banks 
supervisory board they will appoint a lay director and deputy 
director 
police said another banker wanted in connection with italys 
worst postwar banking scandal flew to milan from brazil on tuesday 
and surrendered to authorities 
banker umberto ortolani faces charges of fraudulent bankruptcy 
following the 1982 collapse of banco ambrosiano 
judges investigating the collapse of italys largest private bank 
have charged ortolani with stealing 230 million from the 
milanbased bank 
marcinkus and two lay vatican bank officials were charged with 
being accessories to the bankruptcy and warrants were issued for 
their arrests in 1987 
but the arrests never were carried out italys constitutional 
court ruled a vaticanitalian treaty prevents italian authorities 
from interfering in affairs of the vatican the city that is an 
independent state 
vatican officials denied wrongdoing in the collapse of banco 
ambrosiano but agreed to pay 250 million to its creditors 
new board members of the vatican bank are angelo caloia chairman 
of italys mediocredito lombardo philippe de weck former chairman 
of union bank of switzerland jose a sanchez asiain cochairman of 
spains banco bilbao vizcaya theodor e pietzcker a director of 
west germanys deutsche bank and thomas m macioce former chairman 
and chief executive officer of allied stores corp in new york 
the nominations take effect immediately navarro said 
tuesdays appointments are the latest in sweeping management 
reforms announced in march that also established a special 
commission of five cardinals for the bank which is called the 
institute for religious works 
the reforms abolished the post of president held since 1969 by 
the 67yearold marcinkus a native of cicero ill however 
marcinkus retains another post equivalent to deputy governor of the 
vatican state 
navarro said the new board members have helped the church in the 
past he said macioce has advised new york archbishop john j 
oconnor on financial matters 
the vatican banks balance sheet is secret but navarro said the 
board could decide to make it public 
board members have broad responsibility to decide longterm 
investment strategy and give guidelines to the director who has 
charge of daily management 
