<TEXT>
the united states can conduct star wars 
research and development far more cheaply than the bush 
administration is proposing acording to a congressional report 
released tuesday 
the three types of budget options described in the congressional 
budget office report would cost 113 billion to 184 billion from 
1990 to 1994 rather than the 311 billion proposed by president 
bush for the same period 
if we spend billions on strategic defense that does not really 
defend us and siphon these billions from the budgets of fighter 
planes ships tanks and personnel we may not make the country 
more secure said rep john spratt dsc a member of the house 
armed services committee who requested the report for this 
reason the cbo report bears careful study 
bush cut spending on the strategic defense initiative to 46 
billion for fiscal 1990 down from the 59 billion proposed by 
former president reagan 
defense secretary dick cheney has also said bush will shift the 
focus of star wars from deployment sometime in the 1990s to research 
on a more advanced system known as brilliant pebbles consisting 
of thousands of orbiting satellites 
under the reports first option the united states would be 
protected against a soviet breakthrough in technology or the 
kremlins deployment of a strategic defense system 
total spending would range from 113 billion to 145 billion 
and the option would be in compliance with the antiballistic 
missile treaty the report said 
the second option estimated at a cost of about 17 billion 
would enable the united states to defend parts of the country 
against a limited nuclear attack caused by an accident that option 
may comply with the abm treaty the report said 
the third option costing about 184 billion would provide a 
larger strategic defense system that would protect landbased 
missiles housed in silos such as the mx and midgetman 
the report estimates did not include the cost of procuring the 
system 
