the senate commerce committee approved 
legislation on tuesday to improve highway safety by toughening 
penalties for drug sales at truck stops and highway rest areas 
the legislation also would prohibit trucking companies from 
hauling hazardous materials and bus companies from carrying 
passengers if they receive an unsatisfactory safety rating from 
the transportation department 
the measure sent to the full senate provides for doubling and 
tripling of existing penalties for crimes involving drug sales at 
truck stops and rest areas it also would establish minimum jail 
sentences one year for first convictions and three years for 
repeat offenders 
the maximum penalties will vary according to the crime a person 
is charged with 
supporters of the measure say they hope to reduce drug use by 
truck drivers they contend that rest areas and truck stops have 
increasingly become markets for drug trafficking 
the bill also would require the transportation department to make 
random inspections of vehicles that are removed from service because 
of safety problems take enforcement actions against companies for 
serious safety violations and establish a regulation to improve 
truck braking performance 
this is a major step to end big truck accidents that tie up 
major highways and claim more than 5000 lives a year and cost the 
public millions of dollars said david f snyder counsel for the 
american insurance association which represents companies providing 
onethird of the insurance to the nations commercial truckers 
