<TEXT>
mix arthur miller with neil simon and a bit of 
jule styne and youll get the loman family picnic by donald 
margulies 
this odd yet imaginative domestic freeforall which opened 
tuesday at manhattan theater clubs stage ii keeps the audience 
offbalance for most of the evening as the story switches from low 
comedy to high drama to hardsell musical comedy the changes of 
gear could be unsettling but the playwright and director barnet 
kellman manage to keep everything spinning for much of the time 
on the day i was married the world showed every sign of coming 
to an end says the plays 38yearold heroine doris it didnt 
and neither did her marriage to a drab lighting fixture salesman 
named herbie 
instead their lives in a middleclass coney island apartment 
building just went on and on the years were highlighted by the 
arrival of two sons stewie and mitchell the play set in 1965 
turns on stewies bar mitzvah and all the problems and pressures it 
produces 
like willy loman in millers death of a salesman doris 
dreams of a better life and actually believes she has found one with 
herbie and like willy who idolized his successful and adventurous 
uncle charlie doris adores her late and lamented aunt marsha who 
died at age 23 the ghost of uncle charlie hovers over millers 
classic aunt marsha a toughtalking sexy young woman does the 
same in the loman family picnic 
doris and herbie dont really talk margulies dialogue between 
husband and wife is a model of noncommunication they dont say 
whats on their minds until it is too late 
the wife focuses her attention on her sons the older stewie 
played with authentic obnoxiousness by judd trichter and the more 
artistic and sensitive mitchell portrayed with charm and grace by 
michael miceli 
instead of a writing a book report on death of a salesman 
mitchell creates a minimusical comedy he calls it willy and 
it bursts upon the stage late in act 2 after the family has had a 
major blowup over the bar mitzvah 
mitchells music for willy is by david shire composer of 
baby and starting here starting now it has the brassy 
uptempo sound of a styne show a style totally at odds with the 
humdrum happenings on stage but thats the point of margulies 
family tale 
the playwright even adds several alternate endings to the play 
imagining what the characters would like to happen and what really 
does its funny and a bit sad at the same time 
marcia jean kurtz gives a marvelously funny and touching 
performance as the mother doris refuses to give up or grow old 
dressed as the bride of frankenstein she goes trick or treating 
with her sons on halloween and cuts up her wedding dress for a 
costume she keeps repeating i love my life i love my life i 
love my life and you believe her 
larry block one of new yorks most underrated character actors 
excels as herbie hes a superb physical comedian and a master of 
timing watch him as he forces himself to eat the diet tuna plate 
doris prepares each evening for him 
kellman has a difficult job separating the fantasies from real 
life but with the help of the imaginative lighting by debra j 
kletter and his hardy troupe of actors he does just that 
out the living room window looms a nondescript apartment 
building much like the highrises that hem in the loman home in 
millers play designer gw mercier has an eye for detail down to 
the familys hideous mediterranean furniture and shag carpeting that 
covers the tiny stage 
the loman family picnic is an unusual play it echoes miller 
simon and styne but it can stand on its own as an original piece of 
theater 
