<TEXT>
fokker the dutch airplane maker 
that is gaining a strong foothold in the competitive north american 
jetliner market is in the final stages of negotiating a contract 
with pan am corp for the purchase of 30 planes a company spokesman 
said tuesday 
the value of the deal which is awaiting approval by pan ams 
board was estimated at 679 million according to industry sources 
here 
the deal involving the sale of up to 30 fuelefficient fokker 
f100 shorthaul jetliners signaled another step in fokkers final 
breakthrough on the american market said spokesman eduard van veen 
after teetering on the brink of bankruptcy because of huge 
research and development costs only 18 months ago fokker now has 
firm orders for 218 f100s as well as 183 options for its f50 
commuter propjet fokker has 98 firm orders and 32 options van veen 
said 
the dutch airplane manufacturer made its biggest deal in the 
united states so far earlier this year when american airlines 
bought 75 f100s and took as many options other us customers are 
usair and braniff airways 
pan am was expected to deploy the new planes in europe for its 
feeder network to london one of the airlines major european hubs 
and for the shuttle services between west berlin and west german 
cities according to van veen 
the latest contract will speed up fokkers search for a second 
assembly line in addition to the one at amsterdams schiphol 
airport which has a capacity of up to 48 planes a year van veen 
said 
although fokker is considering bids to open an assembly line in 
the united states where some commercial jetliner manufacturers are 
suffering from overcapacity the company is believed to be under 
considerable dutch government pressure to concentrate its production 
facilities in the amsterdam area for employment reasons 
a final decision on that issue is expected in three to four 
weeks van veen said 
